Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco – On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a lengthy meeting on February 4 — that day marked the beginning of China's lunar new year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two issued a carefully drafted document spanning 5000 words announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and certainly requires thorough negotiations beforehand.
I was shocked to see Xi seemingly fully delegating to Putin the invasion and war in Ukraine.
He believes that his confirmation this year as China's lifelong ruler is merely a formality, and he is confident about it.
After consolidating all power in his hands, Xi meticulously planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao and Deng.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to achieve his own lifelong dream in an unbelievably brutal manner.
At 70 years old, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a profound mark in Russian history, it must be now or it will never happen.
But his perception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar to blindly follow.
This system is in stark contrast to democratic societies, and this vision distorts the "souls" of emotionally and sentimentally inclined Russian citizens.
In my childhood, I had many interactions with Russian soldiers who had occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know if you ask them, they will share with you their last loaf of bread.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I called my political charity work.
Initially, I established a foundation in my home country Hungary, and subsequently, I actively participated in promoting the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev took office in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and subsequently, in each independent republic.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989 shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre occurred).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise and fully understand his cold and ruthless personality.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB officer, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality, as he has developed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainian speakers who spoke Russian would welcome the Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out they were no different from Ukrainian-speaking citizens.
In the face of what seemed like an overwhelming possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out incredible and heroic resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi provocateurs.
Because Kyiv was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, his argument's first part is not historically unfounded.
But in the second part of his argument, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have had a clearer understanding of the facts.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The events of 2014 enraged him greatly.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
Deep-rooted corruption in contract awards by the Ministry of Defense also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seemed to have lost his mind.
He is determined to punish Ukraine in resistance, and his actions seem to be unbridled.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear plant (now occupied by Russian troops) was also destroyed.
In Mariupol under siege, over 400,000 people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the EU are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine while also trying to purchase MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could alter the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already achieved a miracle in reinforcing Europe's determination and unity.
Meanwhile, it seems that Xi has realized that Putin has strayed.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi reaffirmed that Sino-Russian friendship remained "as solid as a rock," Xi called President Emmanuel Macron of France and Chancellor Olaf Scholz of Germany to express his support for their peacekeeping activities.
He hopes to exercise maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It remains uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
